XIV. “O most divine Calasiris,'’ said Cnemon, “you have initiated me into a holy mystery. But I notice that you

have two or three times called Homer an Egyptian, which perhaps no one has ever heard3 I do not indeed disbelieve it, but, as your statement greatly surprises me, l beg you will not leave it >unex- plained.” “Although it is foreign to my subject, l will endeavour to satisfy you in a few words. l am quite willing that other countries should claim the honour of being the birthplace of Homer3 the wise man’s country is the world; but he was in fact an Egyptian, born at ‘hundred- gated Thebes,’ as he himself calls it; his · father was Mercury, although commonly supposed to be one of the priests of that god.
